<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-781-724  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 781 724.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Oct 10 1989 v3 n36 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sybase serves up Mac front ends for SQL data. (Apple MacintoshStructured Query Language) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Battelle, John.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Sybase Inc has added its first Macintosh front end products toassist users in access of structured query language databases onmainframes and minicomputers.andP;  Sybase's Open Client, previouslyavailable only for Unix and DEC systems, has been ported to theMac.andP;  The company's Open Server product will work complimentary toits SQL Server transaction processing database, shipping data fromdisparate platforms into one system.andP;  Mac versions of the OpenClient development tools are known as Mac DB-Library and HyperDB-Library, a HyperCard interface to SQL server.andP;  The programswill sell for $195 each.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Sybase Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (computer programs)Hyper DB library (PROGRAM DEVELOPMENT SOFTWARE) (productintroduction)Mac DB Library (PROGRAM DEVELOPMENT SOFTWARE) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Program Development ToolsConnectivityData Base Management SystemsStructured Query Language.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Libraries for MPW, HyperCard dueandM;By John BattelleandM;New York -- Sybase Inc. rolled out its latest developments in multiplatformdatabase connectivity here last week, and heading the list are its first-everofferings for the Mac.andM;The Emeryville, Calif.-based relational database vendor announced Version 4.0of its SQL Server transaction processing database and introduced acomplementary connectivity product, Open Server, that the company says willtie together disparate data and platforms into one fluid client/server-basedsystem.andM;The new Mac product consists of two versions of Sybase's Open Client softwaredevelopment tool, previously available for Unix and Digital Equipment Corp.andO;environments.andP;  Hyper DB-Library uses HyperCard to interface to SQL Server,while Mac DB-Library for MPW (Macintosh Programmer's Workshop) C can be usedto integrate other Mac applications or to create stand-alone front-endapplications.andP;  Both are intended as tools for MIS or database programmerslooking to integrate the Mac with Sybase's on-line high-volume transactiondatabases.andM;Sybase users contacted said that Mac support adds a much-needed client/serverarchitecture to the graphical strengths of the Mac.andP;  Client/server topologiesuse personal computers as &quot;client&quot; front ends for manipulating and displayingdata, while back-end workstations or minicomputers store and retrieve thedata.andM;&quot;The only way we could serve our local customers was with a database based ona client/server architecture,&quot; said Steve Paschall, director of the Orientprogram for US West in Aurora, Colo.andM;Paschall is overseeing the migration of US West's Yellow Pages productionsystem -- spread over 14 states and 35 locations -- from a mainframe-basedsystem to one based on the Mac's publishing capabilities and Sybase's SQLserver running on Hewlett-Packard workstations.andP;  &quot;The data must be local sowe can turn layout jobs around in 24 hours.andP;  The Sybase/Mac solution was theonly way to go.&quot;andM;&quot;We would have had to give up our Macs if Sybase hadn't come along,&quot; saidDavid Baron, director of product development at August International inOrange, Calif.andP;  Baron said he had hit a wall using Mac-based databases totrack large amounts of client data.andM;Sybase's SQL Server and Open Server run on any computer that supports TCP/IPor DECnet protocols, including Sun, Hewlett-Packard, NeXT, DEC (VMS) and IBM.andO;SQL Server also supports IBM's OS/2 Presentation Manager, but the OS/2version of SQL Server will not be compatible with Sybase's new Mac softwareuntil protocol differences among the Mac, OS/2 and TCP/IP are ironed out,according to Ron Arons, product manager at Sybase.andP;  &quot;There are severalcompanies, including 3Com, Microsoft and ourselves, looking to address that,&quot;he said.andP;  He promised a solution by the middle of next year.andM;Both Hyper DB-Library and DB-Library for MPW will ship this month for $195each.andM;Sybase Inc. is located at 6475 Christie Ave., Emeryville, Calif.andP;  94608;(415) 596-3500.andP;  n</TEXT></DOC>